WEBVTT

00:01.340 --> 00:07.180
It's a long story. Part 1. Judy Parker is 22.

00:08.780 --> 00:12.280
She is a medical student. Judy is intelligent

00:12.280 --> 00:16.400
and very pretty, with a good sense of humor. She

00:16.400 --> 00:19.660
is a nice woman. Her boyfriend's name

00:19.660 --> 00:24.900
is Sam Watson. Sam is 27. He works in a

00:24.900 --> 00:29.200
bank as assistant manager. He is good looking but

00:29.200 --> 00:32.720
he is not a very nice man. Judy loves Sam

00:32.720 --> 00:38.340
very much. Sam loves money, cars, good food, whiskey,

00:38.780 --> 00:47.700
travel and beautiful women. It's a long story. Part 2.

00:49.500 --> 00:52.380
Judy is worried. She doesn't know where Sam

00:52.380 --> 00:56.300
is. The bank manager doesn't know where Sam is either.

00:57.100 --> 01:00.800
He is very worried. Sam is in

01:00.800 --> 01:03.860
Brazil, in a small town on the coast near Rio

01:03.860 --> 01:07.480
de Janeiro, with 50,000 pounds of the bank's money.

01:08.700 --> 01:11.180
He is sitting in a barn near the beach, drinking

01:11.180 --> 01:13.840
a large martini and writing a letter to Judy.

01:15.460 --> 01:24.880
It's a long story. Part 3. Rio Tuesday. Darling Judy.

01:26.300 --> 01:29.720
Well, here I am in Brazil. It's very warm

01:29.720 --> 01:33.480
here and the sea is nice for swimming. The women

01:33.480 --> 01:36.800
here are very beautiful and very, very friendly.

01:36.800 --> 01:41.880
But I miss you, Judy. Please come and stay with

01:41.880 --> 01:45.760
me in Brazil. Can you take the 1325 flight

01:45.760 --> 01:49.500
from London to Rio on April the 14th? I'll meet

01:49.500 --> 01:55.480
you at the airport. All my love, Sam. It's a

01:55.480 --> 01:56.180
long story.

01:57.880 --> 02:02.860
Part 4. Judy is at home. She lives in a

02:02.860 --> 02:07.800
small flat near the bank. It's not very nice. She's

02:07.800 --> 02:08.160
in the living

02:08.160 --> 02:12.000
room drinking a cup of coffee and thinking. Judy is

02:12.000 --> 02:14.260
very worried because she doesn't know what to do.

02:15.360 --> 02:18.140
She loves Sam and she doesn't want to tell the

02:18.140 --> 02:21.160
police where he is. But she doesn't want to go

02:21.160 --> 02:21.460
to Rio

02:21.460 --> 02:27.620
either. She wants a quiet life. Judy goes to the

02:27.620 --> 02:31.220
window and looks out. There's a police car in the

02:31.220 --> 02:31.500
street.

02:32.620 --> 02:37.080
Two big policemen are walking towards her house. It's a

02:37.080 --> 02:40.300
long story. Part 5.

02:41.580 --> 02:49.020
Hello. Is that Croxton 43122? Dr. Wagner? Listen, Dr. Wagner.

02:49.620 --> 02:52.900
This is Judy. Yes. Judy Parker. Listen.

02:53.840 --> 02:57.600
I'm in very bad trouble. Can you help? Trouble with

02:57.600 --> 03:00.960
Sam and the bank and the police. I haven't got

03:00.960 --> 03:01.840
time to explain.

03:01.840 --> 03:06.820
Yes. Okay. Please come to my house at once with

03:06.820 --> 03:09.440
your car as fast as you can. It's really urgent.

03:11.040 --> 03:17.160
23. Carlton Road. Turn right up the station and it's

03:17.160 --> 03:20.360
the second street on your left. Please, Holly.

03:21.420 --> 03:25.060
Oh, and come to the back door. It's a long

03:25.060 --> 03:26.840
story.

03:26.840 --> 03:30.940
Part 6. Dr. Wagner and Judy are on their way

03:30.940 --> 03:32.880
to the airport in Dr. Wagner's car.

03:34.060 --> 03:37.060
There is enough a car behind them with a pretty

03:37.060 --> 03:41.740
blue lamp on top. Dr. Wagner accelerates and the police

03:41.740 --> 03:42.460
car disappears.

03:47.340 --> 03:51.580
It's not the problem, Judy. I can't explain. It's too

03:51.580 --> 03:52.100
complicated.

03:53.040 --> 03:57.120
I know what it is. It's that son. I did

03:57.120 --> 04:00.300
like him at all. He's a very dishonest young man.

04:00.740 --> 04:03.660
Sam is my boyfriend and I love him. He has

04:03.660 --> 04:05.480
sensitive eyes and beautiful hands.

04:05.480 --> 04:13.580
Sam. It's a long story. Part 7.

04:17.440 --> 04:21.960
Please go to the other hand. First class or tourist?

04:22.540 --> 04:23.400
Oh, tourist, please.

04:24.560 --> 04:27.880
Judy checks in and goes through passport control to the

04:27.880 --> 04:31.580
departure gate. On the plane she finds a seat by

04:31.580 --> 04:31.960
the window.

04:33.260 --> 04:37.240
A young man comes and sits down by her. Judy

04:37.240 --> 04:41.420
looks at him. He is tall and dark, about 25

04:41.420 --> 04:43.360
and very well dressed.

04:44.460 --> 04:48.400
Judy is not interested in him. He has dark brown

04:48.400 --> 04:53.080
eyes, a straight nose, a wide humorous mouth and strong

04:53.080 --> 04:55.380
brown hands with long sensitive fingers.

04:56.290 --> 05:00.540
He is incredibly handsome. Judy looks out of the window.

05:04.200 --> 05:07.840
It's a long story. Part 8.

05:12.160 --> 05:16.760
Excuse me. Would you like a drink? Oh, yes. Thank

05:16.760 --> 05:18.580
you very much. Are we still pleased?

05:19.540 --> 05:22.440
The young man gave Judy her drink and smiled at

05:22.440 --> 05:27.500
her. He had an incredibly attractive smile. He really looked

05:27.500 --> 05:31.000
very nice, calm, friendly and kind.

05:32.620 --> 05:36.200
Perhaps he's a doctor, she thought. A surgeon with those

05:36.200 --> 05:41.160
strong, sensitive hands. Or perhaps an artist. Or a musician.

05:42.600 --> 05:47.320
Yes. He looked like an artist. She looked at him

05:47.320 --> 05:54.680
again and smiled. What time is it, please? 25. Thank

05:54.680 --> 05:54.940
you.

05:57.640 --> 06:02.700
He smiled at her. She smiled back at him. He

06:02.700 --> 06:06.220
smiled again. He took a down out of his pocket,

06:06.580 --> 06:08.720
stood up and walked to the front of the plane.

06:11.740 --> 06:15.240
It's a long story. Part 9.

06:16.580 --> 06:21.400
Good afternoon. This is your hijacker speaking. We are now

06:21.400 --> 06:24.820
flying at 550 miles per hour at the height of

06:24.820 --> 06:28.960
29,000 feet. In approximately one and a half hours,

06:29.640 --> 06:33.260
we will be over the north of Scotland. I wish

06:33.260 --> 06:34.600
you a pleasant flight.

06:36.660 --> 06:41.260
Judy's head was going round and round. First Sam, then

06:41.260 --> 06:45.160
the police, and now the hijacker. Where would it all

06:45.160 --> 06:51.260
end? Life was really much too complicated. She drank her

06:51.260 --> 06:55.780
whiskey. They didn't make any difference. She looked out of

06:55.780 --> 06:59.720
the window. The sky was full of big, dark clouds.

07:00.920 --> 07:01.960
So was her head.

07:03.440 --> 07:07.960
Sometime later, the plane started going down. The pilot's door

07:07.960 --> 07:11.280
opened and the hijacker came out, still holding his gun.

07:12.680 --> 07:16.920
He walked up to her and smiled. You know, you're

07:16.920 --> 07:21.000
in here extremely beautiful. Come on, put on your parachute.

07:22.080 --> 07:31.040
Judy fainted. It's a long story. Part 10. Judy opened

07:31.040 --> 07:31.520
her eyes.

07:32.600 --> 07:35.780
The sun was shining and the cool wind was blowing

07:35.780 --> 07:39.100
on her face. She felt very light and happy.

07:39.820 --> 07:43.680
Hold on, Mom. A hundred feet above Loch Ness. Can

07:43.680 --> 07:46.180
you swim? Judy fainted again.

07:48.380 --> 07:50.980
When she opened her eyes, she was lying on the

07:50.980 --> 07:53.680
bank of the lock with her head on her parachute.

07:55.200 --> 07:56.440
I'll only to introduce myself.

07:57.500 --> 08:01.180
Meaning it was Jasper McDonald. Why did you hijack the

08:01.180 --> 08:05.900
plane? It's my birthday. Now let's go to my castle

08:05.900 --> 08:07.680
and find some dry clothes.

08:11.780 --> 08:17.680
It's a long story. Part 11. It didn't take long

08:17.680 --> 08:21.460
to get to Jasper's castle. It was an enormous building.

08:22.180 --> 08:25.160
About half a mile from Loch Ness with tall towers,

08:25.740 --> 08:28.880
bottle mints and a moat, and at least 200 rooms.

08:29.320 --> 08:32.720
What a play! Well, it's not much, but it's home.

08:33.760 --> 08:36.300
Let me show you to your room, and I'll see

08:36.300 --> 08:38.020
if I can find you some of my sister's clothes.

08:39.540 --> 08:42.100
Judy room was about ten minutes' walk from the main

08:42.100 --> 08:45.520
entrance, up a lot of stairs, and along a lot

08:45.520 --> 08:45.820
of corridors.

08:47.220 --> 08:50.880
It was beautiful. They created a light-blued line look

08:50.880 --> 08:53.120
with some wonderful pieces of antique furniture.

08:53.120 --> 08:56.560
There was a splendid view of the lock and the

08:56.560 --> 09:00.760
mountains. This is lovely. How many of you live here?

09:01.060 --> 09:05.200
Just my sister and I, and the ghost, of course.

09:06.420 --> 09:07.240
See you later.

09:10.440 --> 09:16.420
It's a long story. Part 12. Judy had a bath,

09:17.200 --> 09:20.700
and then put on some of Jasper's sister's clothes. They

09:20.700 --> 09:21.500
fitted her perfectly.

09:23.120 --> 09:27.740
She looked at herself in the mirror, smiled, frowned, and

09:27.740 --> 09:28.220
went downstairs.

09:30.980 --> 09:34.320
Hello? Did I tell you how beautiful you are? Yes,

09:34.360 --> 09:34.820
you did.

09:35.920 --> 09:39.260
Fine. Let me show you around the castle before tea.

09:39.760 --> 09:40.920
And I want to go for tea.

09:41.700 --> 09:45.060
This part of the castle is built in 1580. I

09:45.060 --> 09:45.900
want to go to Rio.

09:46.420 --> 09:50.000
This is a portrait of my ancestor Donald McDonald. I'm

09:50.000 --> 09:51.760
going to see my girlfriend's farm.

09:51.760 --> 09:55.100
He's a friend of King James VI. I love him.

09:56.560 --> 10:00.300
James VI? Maybe you've found my girlfriend's farm.

10:00.580 --> 10:05.360
Oh, Sam Watson. You don't want to see him? Yes,

10:05.560 --> 10:07.360
I do. No, you don't.

10:08.420 --> 10:12.620
This is a portrait of my ancestor McDonald McDonald. How

10:12.620 --> 10:15.840
do you know Sam? He's a friend of King Robert

10:15.840 --> 10:16.160
Deuce.

10:16.160 --> 10:21.600
Sam? No, you fool. McDonald. You don't want to see

10:21.600 --> 10:26.940
Sam? You'll just stay here with me. I love you.

10:28.120 --> 10:30.400
Out of a door came an old man with white

10:30.400 --> 10:34.320
hair and a very strange clothes. He was carrying his

10:34.320 --> 10:37.920
head under his arm. He looked very like the portrait.

10:38.740 --> 10:44.980
The ghost? You don't want to go and see Sam?

10:46.200 --> 10:49.580
You want to stay here with Jasper?

10:53.800 --> 10:55.340
It's a long story.

10:56.700 --> 11:00.860
Part 13. Sam Watson was standing at the arrival's gate

11:00.860 --> 11:04.880
at Rio Airport holding a bunch of flowers. He was

11:04.880 --> 11:05.160
worried.

11:06.420 --> 11:09.940
Judas Plain was three hours late and nobody knew why.

11:11.540 --> 11:13.780
Sam walked over to the bar and had a drink.

11:14.940 --> 11:18.200
He walked back to the arrival's gate. No news.

11:19.360 --> 11:21.360
He walked back to the bar and had a rubber

11:21.360 --> 11:28.880
drink. Still no news. Back to the bar. Two hours

11:28.880 --> 11:32.820
and eight drinks later Judas Plain landed.

11:33.640 --> 11:37.220
And after another half hour the passengers started coming out.

11:38.500 --> 11:40.460
Sam smiled and looked for Judas.

11:41.840 --> 11:46.880
After a time he stopped smiling. Finally the last passenger

11:46.880 --> 11:52.200
came through. It wasn't Judas. Sam said a big bad

11:52.200 --> 11:56.920
word. What had happened? He went over to the information

11:56.920 --> 11:57.400
desk.

11:59.560 --> 12:03.880
My name is Sam Watson. Have you got any messages

12:03.880 --> 12:04.480
for me?

12:05.080 --> 12:08.620
No. A terrible message from Scotland.

12:10.700 --> 12:17.600
Mr. Sam Watson, Rio Airport. Haven't my holiday? Don't come

12:17.600 --> 12:20.220
back. Love Jasper McDonald.

12:21.160 --> 12:25.640
Sam said another big bad word. Tore up the paper

12:25.640 --> 12:29.140
and gave the flowers to the stewardess. What time is

12:29.140 --> 12:30.240
the next plane to London?

12:31.320 --> 12:35.200
Behind Sam a tall beautiful girl was listening to his

12:35.200 --> 12:40.300
conversation. When she heard the word London, she smiled.

12:42.900 --> 12:48.500
It's a long story. Part 14. As the night plane

12:48.500 --> 12:54.340
took off, Sam closed his eyes. He loved travelling but

12:54.340 --> 12:56.020
he was always a little afraid of flying.

12:57.460 --> 13:00.600
He couldn't really understand how the plane stayed up in

13:00.600 --> 13:04.300
the air. Also he was worried about what could happen

13:04.300 --> 13:04.620
to him.

13:06.140 --> 13:08.500
Would there be detectives waiting for him at London airport?

13:10.520 --> 13:14.620
It was crazy to leave Brazil. In Brazil there was

13:14.620 --> 13:17.020
some, freedom and beautiful women.

13:17.900 --> 13:20.280
He could have been happy for years with his £50

13:20.280 --> 13:25.920
,000. In Britain there was a role in trouble, policeman

13:25.920 --> 13:28.140
and a strong chance of prison.

13:29.900 --> 13:35.320
But he had to see Judy. Judy was different. Judy

13:35.320 --> 13:40.320
was special. Sam smiled and opened his eyes.

13:41.720 --> 13:45.560
Next to him, they were sitting a tall, incredibly beautiful

13:45.560 --> 13:54.260
girl. Hello. My name's Sam. I know. My name's Detective

13:54.260 --> 13:55.100
Sam in London.

13:55.960 --> 14:04.160
Sam closed his eyes again. It's a long story. Part

14:04.160 --> 14:04.620
15.

14:06.020 --> 14:08.580
When Judy woke up the next morning, the sun was

14:08.580 --> 14:12.060
shining, the birds were singing and everything was beautiful.

14:13.340 --> 14:18.060
Her room was lovely and she felt fine. There was

14:18.060 --> 14:20.240
a muck on the door and then walked the ghost,

14:20.840 --> 14:21.860
carrying a cup of tea.

14:22.500 --> 14:24.240
Do you sleep well?

14:25.740 --> 14:29.720
Yes, beautifully. And go to for a wonderful dinner last

14:29.720 --> 14:30.020
night.

14:30.540 --> 14:31.740
The ghost blushed.

14:32.460 --> 14:33.320
No good room.

14:34.860 --> 14:39.620
It was just a sin for you. I am glad

14:39.620 --> 14:41.260
you enjoyed it.

14:42.260 --> 14:47.620
The evening before, after a magnificent dinner cooked by the

14:47.620 --> 14:51.280
ghost, Judy and Jasper had talked far into the night

14:51.280 --> 15:02.180
about life, love, art, death, music, books, travel, philosophy, religion,

15:03.040 --> 15:09.220
politics, economics, astronomy, biochemistry, archaeology,

15:10.220 --> 15:15.020
and many other subjects. Most of all, they had talked

15:15.020 --> 15:19.280
about themselves and when they had said good night, Jasper

15:19.280 --> 15:21.460
had kissed her, very gently.

15:22.380 --> 15:25.840
She could still feel the touch of his lips. What

15:25.840 --> 15:29.720
a perfect evening. Judy smiled at the memory.

15:31.400 --> 15:35.080
She stopped smiling. She had to go to Rio to

15:35.080 --> 15:35.520
see Sam.

15:36.680 --> 15:41.760
Sam was her boyfriend. She loved him. The sun went

15:41.760 --> 15:44.940
behind a cloud. The birds stopped singing.

15:46.280 --> 15:49.840
Judy started getting dressed as fast as she could. It's

15:49.840 --> 15:50.500
a long story.

15:52.120 --> 15:57.520
Part 16. When Sam woke up, he felt terrible. He

15:57.520 --> 15:59.940
had a headache and there was a horrible taste in

15:59.940 --> 16:00.240
his mouth.

16:01.260 --> 16:04.740
He looked out of the window. The sun was shining

16:04.740 --> 16:07.200
and threw a gap in the clouds he could see

16:07.200 --> 16:10.160
the sea. It was a long way down.

16:11.460 --> 16:14.960
Sam shivered and turned to look at Detective Sergeant Honeybone.

16:16.220 --> 16:20.260
She looked fresh and lovely, even more beautiful than even

16:20.260 --> 16:20.800
before.

16:23.100 --> 16:28.380
Good morning. Did you see it now? No. Excuse me.

16:30.520 --> 16:35.160
He got up and walked forward to the toilets. After

16:35.160 --> 16:38.940
watching the shave, Sam felt a little better. He brushed

16:38.940 --> 16:42.220
his hair, put his jacket back on, and looked at

16:42.220 --> 16:45.180
his tongue in the mirror. Not a pretty sight.

16:46.900 --> 16:49.620
Sam put his tongue back in, took out his gun,

16:50.380 --> 16:52.840
and looked at his watch. Time to move.

16:54.500 --> 16:58.320
He came out of the toilet, glanced down quickly, and

16:58.320 --> 17:01.640
then walked to the front of the plane. Opening the

17:01.640 --> 17:03.400
door of the cockpit, he stepped inside.

17:05.340 --> 17:09.020
This is a hijack. Take me to Loch Ness. Oh,

17:09.120 --> 17:12.040
God. Not again. What's this special about Loch Ness?

17:13.100 --> 17:13.920
Jasper McDonald.

17:18.780 --> 17:25.480
It's a long story. Part 17. Judy ran downstairs and

17:25.480 --> 17:29.560
into the dining room. No Jasper. Over the ghost.

17:30.480 --> 17:32.840
Come over here for you.

17:34.960 --> 17:37.120
Would you like some breakfast?

17:38.860 --> 17:39.480
Where's Jasper?

17:40.440 --> 17:41.820
He's gone out.

17:43.640 --> 17:47.260
Oh dear. When did you pay the credit card to

17:47.260 --> 17:47.460
you?

17:48.040 --> 17:49.560
Quickly, she got a note to Jasper.

17:52.240 --> 18:01.200
Jasper, it was wonderful, but I have to go. I'm

18:01.200 --> 18:08.160
sorry. I wanted to say goodbye to you, but perhaps

18:08.160 --> 18:10.780
if you're bitter, like this.

18:12.620 --> 18:19.220
Thank you for a beautiful memory. Judy.

18:21.760 --> 18:25.160
She said goodbye to the ghost, who looked sad, and

18:25.160 --> 18:29.020
walked out of the castle. Not far along the road,

18:29.240 --> 18:29.900
there was a bus stop.

18:31.300 --> 18:33.240
If she could get to him the mess before lunch,

18:34.020 --> 18:36.440
she could catch the afternoon plane to London, and buy

18:36.440 --> 18:38.880
some new clothes before catching the night flight to Rio.

18:39.960 --> 18:44.140
Tomorrow morning, she could be in Sam's arms. How wonderful.

18:45.640 --> 18:46.780
Judy started crying.

18:48.860 --> 18:51.140
At the bus stop, Judy read the timetable.

18:52.780 --> 18:56.120
Busy threw the mess around every three hours, but she

18:56.120 --> 18:58.320
was lucky, but it was one in 20 minutes.

19:00.100 --> 19:03.080
As she stood waiting, she looked out over the lake.

19:04.200 --> 19:06.880
A few hundred yards away, there was a man fishing

19:06.880 --> 19:09.760
in a boat. She could hear him singing in the

19:09.760 --> 19:10.660
clear still air.

19:11.760 --> 19:15.360
He had a wonderful voice. The voice said Judy recognized,

19:16.560 --> 19:18.840
and he was singing an old Scottish love song.

19:20.300 --> 19:21.160
It was Jasper.

19:23.040 --> 19:26.360
Tears came into Judy's eyes, and she looked away from

19:26.360 --> 19:28.460
the boat, up into the peaceful sky.

19:30.000 --> 19:32.720
High above a lot of nests, a golden eagle was

19:32.720 --> 19:33.520
flying in circles.

19:34.680 --> 19:37.660
There were pretty little clouds looking like spushes of white

19:37.660 --> 19:41.820
paint against the deep blue, and two parachutes.

19:44.500 --> 19:47.760
It's a long story, part 18.

19:49.280 --> 19:51.960
Sam and Detective Sergeant Honeyburne hit the water together.

19:53.100 --> 19:54.640
Sam went under, and came up.

19:56.120 --> 19:58.020
He shouted, going under again.

19:58.520 --> 19:59.640
I can't swim!

20:00.360 --> 20:02.520
He shouted as he came up again and went under

20:02.520 --> 20:03.460
for the third time.

20:04.980 --> 20:07.180
Sam's life passed in front of his eyes as he

20:07.180 --> 20:10.700
went down, down, down into the green water.

20:11.420 --> 20:15.000
His childhood in London, visiting his mother and father in

20:15.000 --> 20:20.420
prison, his first girlfriend, his first bank robbery, Judy.

20:20.420 --> 20:24.880
Judy. He had never seen her again.

20:25.640 --> 20:29.220
Don't worry, you lovely man! I'm an Olympic fan of

20:29.220 --> 20:30.040
me, the gold medals!

20:31.200 --> 20:34.880
Detective Sergeant Honeyburne swam over to Sam with beautiful, strong

20:34.880 --> 20:35.640
strokes.

20:36.260 --> 20:38.180
Put him under the arms as he came up again,

20:38.840 --> 20:40.360
and started pulling him towards the boat.

20:42.360 --> 20:43.040
How's the bell?

20:44.240 --> 20:46.280
What are you doing here, and why have you got

20:46.280 --> 20:47.000
sailing with you?

20:47.640 --> 20:49.300
Please, the last person I went to see.

20:50.600 --> 20:54.960
It's a long story. I'll tell you later. Wait, why

20:54.960 --> 20:56.160
don't you Sam, the kiss of life?

20:56.940 --> 21:00.080
I don't need the kiss of life. Are you what

21:00.080 --> 21:00.340
you do?

21:04.160 --> 21:05.220
It's a long story.

21:06.700 --> 21:07.380
Part 19.

21:10.340 --> 21:13.420
All right. As it is, we'd better go back to

21:13.420 --> 21:15.040
the castle and find you some dry clothes.

21:16.920 --> 21:19.280
Pity, who's hoping for a quiet mamaing's fishing?

21:20.180 --> 21:22.020
Jasper rode the boat over to the bank of the

21:22.020 --> 21:23.020
lock, and they got out.

21:24.060 --> 21:27.620
Detective Sergeant Honeyburne picked up soon in her beautiful, strong

