27:08.020 --> 27:12.260
And local folk tales, going back centuries, speak of water

27:12.260 --> 27:16.000
horses, and water bulls, and haliting Loch Ness.

27:17.600 --> 27:21.860
Scientists have seriously suggested that large creatures may have been

27:21.860 --> 27:25.160
stranded in the Loch when 60 million years ago it

27:25.160 --> 27:26.260
was cut off from the sea.

27:27.640 --> 27:32.320
Perhaps their descendants live there still, but despite hazy photographs,

27:32.840 --> 27:36.840
mostly highly magnified of strange humps in the water, there

27:36.840 --> 27:38.880
